\f0\fs26 \cf0 \cb2 1) update to \'93Credential Management\'94 at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.eucalyptus.com/docs/eucalyptus/4.1.0/index.html#security-guide/security_bp_access.html"}}{\fldrslt https://www.eucalyptus.com/docs/eucalyptus/4.1.0/index.html#security-guide/security_bp_access.html}}\
Protection and careful management of user credentials (passwords, access keys, X.509 certificates, and key pairs) is critical to cloud security. When dealing with credentials, we recommend:\
- Limit the number of active credentials and do not create more credentials than needed.  \cb1 Using 
\f1 euca_conf --get-credentials
\f0  creates a new set of X.509 certificates on each request. Avoid unnecessary use of this command and use 
\f1 euare-useraddkey
\f0  and 
\f1 euare-usercreatecert
\f0  or euare-useraddcert instead to get a specific set of credentials.\cb2 \
- Only create users and credentials for the interfaces that you will actually use. For example, if a user is only going to use the Management Console, do not create credentials access keys for that user.\
- Regularly check for active credentials using EUARE commands and remove unused credentials. Ideally, only one pair of active credentials should be available at any time.\
- Rotate credentials regularly and delete old credentials as soon as possible. Credentials can be created and deleted using EUARE commands, such as euare-useraddkey and euare-userdelkey.\
- When rotating credentials, there is an option to deactivate, instead of removing, existing access/secret keys and X.509 certificates. Requests made using deactivated credentials will no longer be accepted, but the credentials will remain in the Eucalyptus database and can be restored if needed. You can deactive credentials using 
\f1 euare-usermodkey
\f0  and 
\f1 euare-usermodcert
\f0 .\
